John Edward: Language Skills Essential for Global Citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have a zipper of academic excellence, and this was continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which were only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community enterprises.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their position as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we see world languages continue as a popular and desirable subject choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher grade A.
The data, collected from SCIS’s 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 of those who studied French, and 63 of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now have the same prestige as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools’ curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Professions and Skills found in 2014 that of the reasons employees provide why they struggle to fill jobs, 17 percent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, in the future they will have a real advantage with such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is so important to invest in today’s language education.
Knowing several languages, especially those from developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of getting meaningful work.
In Scotland, every school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will be taught that are considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still immensely important for the country’s future, and therefore must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages really need to be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s young people.
It is very fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools.
