A new course at Harvard University this year lets all of its undergraduate students get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-driven “all-night sessions.”
An academic has found that students at the world’s top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of how to look after themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he is believed to be the first of his kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this first, in my senior year?'
She said no one had told her yet how important sleep is – which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented for the first time that year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it found that students were severely deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a few interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, workout shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep rhythm.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know this will not change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health impact of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride of “studying all night” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough good quality sleep, a student’s “secret weapon” should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said – even to avoid it from putting on weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after running one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and being aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
