The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and soprano dwarf bat as well as the brown long ear and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations on the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also do mobile surveys using hand-held indicators.
Expert clan channels of all surveys will check the regularity of the bat screams and determine which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor to NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how it is used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as pasture creation and how to best manage forest lands for bats and other associated species.
Fleas populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by building and development work that affects sleeping and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as well as flying paper and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren’t blind.
But because of their nighttime hunting activities, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-orientation technique to point out goggas and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained experts who regularly do surveys and sleeping spot inspections and sometimes perform rescues.
The organization even established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson said the estate is the ideal site for them.
“Here at Threave we have a wonderful area for bats,” he said.
"We have the old buildings, many lace trees and all the good habitat.
But there’s so much about bats that’s still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He emphasizes the need to look for bats before maintenance in properties is done because it is possible that unwitting destruction of a single birthplace could mean the death of up to 400 females and young ones and could eradicate an entire local population.
Fleas are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or prevent them or destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to jump in to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species, we don’t know how their populations go.”
